# Scenario: eUICC PROFILE FALLBACK NOT TRIGGERED — Quectel BG770A with Hologram
# Hyper SIM (eUICC). Active profile (carrier A) lost network. Fallback profile
# (carrier B) is provisioned on the eUICC but the device hasn't switched.
# Conductor-relevant: the whole reason Conductor exists is to handle this
# scenario automatically via policy. This fixture represents what the failure
# looks like on a SIM that ISN'T enrolled in a Conductor failover policy
# (or the policy didn't fire).
# Key signals:
#   +QESIM: "list",1,"...341234012",1   profile 1 active (state=1)
#   +QESIM: "list",2,"...341234020",0   profile 2 inactive (state=0)
#   +QESIM: "active",1                  active profile = profile 1
#   +COPS=? returns no networks         active profile sees no usable network
#   +CEREG: 0,2                         searching, will not register
#   +CSQ: 99,99                         no signal on currently selected RAT/PLMN
# Diagnosis: the active profile's home/roaming agreements don't reach this
# location, but a usable profile sits idle on the eUICC. Without orchestration,
# the SIM stays stuck on the wrong profile indefinitely.
# Customer guidance:
#   IMMEDIATE FIX (single SIM):
#     - From Hologram dashboard SIM detail page, manually switch the active
#       profile to profile 2.
#     - OR via Conductor API (alpha):
#         POST /conductor/v1/sims/{iccid}/profile/switch
#         { "target_profile_index": 2 }
#     - Wait ~30-60 seconds for the eUICC to apply the switch and reboot the
#       SIM session. Modem will re-attach on the new profile.
#   FLEET-LEVEL FIX (the right answer):
#     - Define a Conductor failover policy:
#         "If a SIM cannot register on its active profile for >5 minutes,
#          switch to next available profile in priority order."
#     - This single policy resolves this fault class for all current and future
#       SIMs in the fleet without per-incident intervention.
# Triage flag: for any eUICC SIM, check active vs available profiles BEFORE
# debugging the modem or carrier side. A policy-driven fleet should self-heal;
# if it doesn't, the policy is the bug, not the device.

AT+CPIN?
+CPIN: READY
OK
AT+CGSN
350201234567890
OK
AT+QESIM="list"
+QESIM: "list",1,"89001012012341234012",1
+QESIM: "list",2,"89001012012341234020",0
OK
AT+QESIM="active"
+QESIM: "active",1
OK
AT+COPS=?
+COPS: ,,,(0-4),(0,1,2)
OK
AT+CEREG?
+CEREG: 0,2
OK
AT+CSQ
+CSQ: 99,99
OK
AT+QENG="servingcell"
+QENG: "servingcell","SEARCH"
OK
